title: Revamp documentation system
body:
b"I basically ripped out the old documentation system using sphinx which was more confusing than actually helpful and replaced it with [`mkdocs`](https://github.com/tomchristie/mkdocs). This new system has the following benefits:
- Documentation can be written in `markdown` instead of `rst`.
- Documentation can automatically be published on the gh-pages branch using `mkdocs gh-deploy` where it will be visible through [zipline.io](http://zipline.io)
- Automatic conversion of IPython notebooks: This allows the documentation to be written and the included/published as an IPython notebook.

For the current look, see here: http://zipline.io/

There are still some markdown quirks (https://github.com/tomchristie/mkdocs/issues/310) but I don't think it's a huge deal. I currently link `README.md` to be the title page.

I also removed pretty much everything of the prior documentation just because it was obsolete and I think it's better to have a fresh start.

We should then start writing IPython Notebooks to document zipline features.
"

title: WIP: Lot (don't merge)
labels: [{'id': 138524488, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwxMzg1MjQ0ODg=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/quantopian/zipline/labels/In%20Progress', 'name': 'In Progress', 'color': '00ffff', 'default': False, 'description': None}, {'id': 135906301, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwxMzU5MDYzMDE=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/quantopian/zipline/labels/Needs%20Review', 'name': 'Needs Review', 'color': 'eb6420', 'default': False, 'description': None}]
body:
b'Per conversation yesterday with @ehebert and @twiecki, this is a first cut at implementing a tax `lot` object that sits under a `position`.

As much as possible, this is supposed to be a "drop-in" replacement for the existing `Position` object, for illustrative and compatibility purposes. It _should_ work in most cases. The only non-`Position` code that was modified is the `update_position` method of the `PerformancePeriod` class. As a result there's a lot of `Position` code that is probably unnecessary but is kept for compatibility.

There is support for close instructions but I didn't change `order()` to allow them as an argument, so for the moment the default `FIFO` is always used.

Zipline makes a few assumptions that aren't really possible in a tax lot world (but are in its single-position world) like blanket adjustments of `amount` and `cost_basis`.

We can discuss further offline.
'

If a SID hasn't started trading yet, pandas' convention is to use nans.
Before this change, zipline would raise an exception if there were nans in the
input data.

We now skip events where the prices contains a nan and has not been traded
before (in which case forward fill).

Fixes #446.
"

title: Add LIQUIDATION events
body:
b'Securities sometimes stop trading due to delisting, acquisition, maturity, etc. Currently, if users hold positions in those securities, the positions just persist after the security disappears, maintaining their market values. There is no way to close these positions because orders are only executed when trades occur (which, once the security stops trading, is never!). This creates a strong divergence from reality because users can't make use of cash which would be returned to them when the security is liquidated and must use leverage instead.

Proposed solution: a new `DATASOURE_TYPE` called `LIQUIDATION` which looks just like a `TRADE` but differs in two ways:
    1. When `AlgorithmSimulator` encounters a `LIQUIDATION` event, it (a) cancels all open orders for that `sid` on the blotter (because you can't trade it anymore!) and (b) places one more order that closes any open positions.
    2. When `Slippage` encounters a `LIQUIDATION` event, it generates a transaction without regard for commission or volume. (maybe the commission constraint should go?)

Otherwise, liquidation-generated orders/transactions are handled exactly like "normal" ones, to maintain compatibility. The only difference is that when liquidation events appear, all trading is halted and all positions are forcibly closed out.

Usage is simple. Whenever a `DataSource` gets to the last trade of a security, it emits a `LIQUIDATION` event instead of -- or in addition to -- the normal `TRADE` event. Because this is handled on the data source end, users don't need to worry about leaking future knowledge; whenever the security liquidates, the system will process it automatically. Since a LIQUIDATION event can have its own price, a security could be liquidated at 0, par, or some acquisition price regardless of the last observed trade.
'

title: Remove bottleneck caused by unnecessary check of the position index.
body:
b'Instead of checking the positions indexes every time either
`_position_amounts` or `_position_last_sale_prices` is updated, check
and grow the individual Series on each update.

This gain with this patch is by reducing the following bottlenecks:
- Checking both vectors when only one is updated.
- Using try/except to trigger the growth, instead of incurring the cost
  of checking the Index contains on every update.

In testing this change results in about a 33% speedup of the
`update_last_sale` algorithm when run with a buy and hold algorithm with
160 equities, resulting in a 20% speedup overall.
## Further Context

The eventual goal here is to collapse the two position Series into a DataFrame, as prototyped here https://github.com/quantopian/zipline/tree/vectorize-positions, but the gain from this patch had a big enough gain to parts changed that it is worth pulling in before doing more volatile changes.
'

title: Daily returns
body:
b"Changes to calculations to Risk Metrics. 
A few months ago, we made changes to how we calculated the cumulative risk metrics for our backtester (https://www.quantopian.com/posts/corrections-to-cumulative-risk-metrics). Frank Grossman recently pointed out that he found a discrepancy between the 12 month Zipline metrics and the overall risk metrics that the backtester was showing. We found that the difference came from how we were calculating average daily returns. Before we were using cumulative returns divided by the total number of trading days. We found that this served well for short periods of time (e.g. 12 months) but often overstated the returns when it came to backtest periods of greater than a year. Now we've switched to using a method widely incorporated throughout the industry and that's to use the arithmetic mean to calculate daily returns, so simply put, we are taking the average of daily returns to give us back the mean daily return used to calculate our risk metrics. The actual calculations of the risk metrics (Sharpe, Sortino, Information) remain the same as it was before in this post (https://www.quantopian.com/posts/corrections-to-cumulative-risk-metrics), only the annualized average returns used for the calculations have changed. 

With the new way of calculating daily mean return() (daily_returns.mean()), every metric associated will have differing values:
Alpha
Sharpe
Sortino
Information
Beta remains the same
"

title: History cleanup rebase
body:
b"Overhaul the core HistoryContainer logic to be more robust to changing
universes.
## Major Changes
- Remove `return_frame` cache.  The original purpose of using
  return_frames was to avoid having to create new DataFrames on each
  iteration of handle_data, but we ended up having to copy the return
  frames anyway because user code could mutate the frames in place.
  Removing the return_frames reduces unnecessary copying, and reduces
  the logic of `get_history` to just forward-filling and concatenating
  two DataFrames.
- Use a `MultiIndex`ed DataFrame to represent
  `last_known_prior_values`.  This makes lookups faster and greatly
  simplifies the logic of adding and dropping sids.
- HistoryContainer no longer attempts to determine its universe based on
  the contents of its internal buffers.  The TradingAlgorithm
  controlling the container is now responsible for explicitly calling
  `add_sids` or `drop_sids` when securities enter or leave the
  algorithm's universe.  These methods, along with the internal
  `_realign` method, provide a clean interface for changing the universe
  of securities managed by the container.
- Refactor index mutation logic in `RollingPanel` into a
  `MutableIndexRollingPanel` subclass.  Maintenance of the old behavior
  is regrettably necessary to support `BatchTransform`.
- Refactor shared logic from `roll` and `get_history` into a single
  `aggregate_ohlcv_panel` method that's responsible for collapsing an
  OHLCV buffer into a frame.
"

title: ENH: new api method: add_event
body:
b"This is another version of a time/event management api.

This version allows users to schedule functions to be called with (context, data) args at frequencies other than the backtest frequency. Right now the functions are called before the regular handle_data routine, but after could make sense, it would allow people to set context variables.

Example workflow

```
def func_a(context, data):
    # stuff

def func_b(context, data):
    # other stuff ...

def func_c(context, data):
    # ...

def initialize(context):

    # Set functions to be called every 20 min
    add_event(freq='20T', functions=[func_a, func_b])

    # For once/day events, specify a 'when' function
    add_event(time_func=BeforeClose(minutes=5), functions=[func_c])

def handle_data(context, data):
    # Nothing to be done
    pass
```
"

title: ENH: Support for management of periodic events
body:
b"I have been using a class similar to this for managing events that don't need to occur on every bar that has gotten good feedback from the community in forum posts. This is a first stab at adding it to Zipline.

The primary piece of code is the EventManager class, it helps to manage the trading days between events, and to make sure they don't get executed more than a certain number of times in a trading day. 

The EventManager class accepts a rule function which is called for a final entry decision when all other criteria has been met. I added some common rules that can be used as stand alone checks or as rules for the EventManager. 

Some rules require parameters at initialization so I used classes with **call** methods so they can be passed to the EventManager and work the same as if a function was passed. 

Example Usage: 
This will buy 10 shares of Apple every other day on the 20th and 21st minute minute of the trading day. 

```
after_market_open = EventManager(period=2, 
                                 max_daily_hits=2,
                                 rule_func=AfterOpen(minutes=20))

def initialize(context):
    context.event = after_market_open

def handle_date(context, data):
    dt = get_datetime()
    if context.event.signal(dt):
        print dt
        order('AAPL', 10)
```
"

title: BUG: Fix an issue where dividends are granted a day early.
body:
b"Fixes an issue where `PerformancePeriod.update_dividends` was being called with
incorrect dates in `handle_minute_close` and `handle_market_close`, which
resulted in dividends being granted a day early.  This is primarily a problem
because it causes algorithms to incorrectly receive dividends when the stock in
question is purchased on a dividend's ex_date.  After this change, dividends
are granted only when the algorithm held stock on the market close of the day
before the dividend's ex_date.  This is in line with the following quote from
the SEC's notes on dividend ex_dates:

> If you purchase a stock on its ex-dividend date or after, you will not
> receive the next dividend payment.  Instead, the seller gets the dividend. If
> you purchase before the ex-dividend date, you get the dividend.
"

title: Support for '1m' History Frequency.
body:
b'Overhauls `HistoryContainer` in prep to support '1m' frequency.

Major changes:
- Methods/variables referring to "day" have been renamed/generalized.
  - `current_day_panel` became `buffer_panel`, which is now a `RollingPanel`
  - `prior_day_panel` became a dictionary mapping `Frequency` objects to
    "digest panels", which are instances of `RollingPanel`.
- Hard-coded daily rollover replaced with a notion of a "current window" for
   each unique frequency managed by the panel.
  - When the end of the current window is reached for a given frequency, we
    compute an aggregate bar (code refers to this as a "digest"), which is
    appended to a panel associated with that frequency.
  - Window rollover dates are managed by a pair of dictionaries,
    `cur_window_starts` and `cur_window_closes`.  The `Frequency` class is
    responsible for computing window bounds based on the open/close of the
    previous window.
- Semantic change to the `open_price` field: `open_price` now always
   contains the price of the first trade occurring in the given window.
   Previously it contained the price of the first minute in the window,
   returning NaN it the security happened not to trade in the first minute.
- `price` is now the only field that can be forward-filled. 
'

title: Enforce sentence end double space
body:
b'**DO NOT MERGE, FOR DISCUSSION ONLY**

@twiecki @ssanderson this is a proposal to help standardize formatting via a .dir-locals.el file for Emacs.
Granted, everyone doesn't use Emacs, but the three of us do, and can add similar files for other editors as warranted.

This was inspired by some collision of docstrings between some of my comments and @ssanderson because he was using `fill-paragraph` on the docstrings, which is a good thing to do. The collision was caused by my global setting of `sentence-end-double-space` to `nil`, but we should probably use the default of using double space. So using the .dir-locals.el file to make it explicit.

An open question is what format to use for docstrings, I included a patch to show some docstrings converted to match the PEP-257 value as seen below, since it is the default.
But I am open to other formats, I tend to write in the Django style just by happenstance, but http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0257/#handling-docstring-indentation makes a compelling case.

```
DJANGO:

    """
    Process foo, return bar.
    """

    """
    Process foo, return bar.

    If processing fails throw ProcessingError.
    """

ONETWO:

    """Process foo, return bar."""

    """
    Process foo, return bar.

    If processing fails throw ProcessingError.

    """

PEP-257:

    """Process foo, return bar."""

    """Process foo, return bar.

    If processing fails throw ProcessingError.

    """

PEP-257-NN:

    """Process foo, return bar."""

    """Process foo, return bar.

    If processing fails throw ProcessingError.
    """

SYMMETRIC:

    """Process foo, return bar."""

    """
    Process foo, return bar.

    If processing fails throw ProcessingError.
    """
```
'

title: One Minute History Groundwork
body:
b'Overhauls `HistoryContainer` in prep for support of more than one frequency.

Major changes:
- Methods/variables referring to "day" have been renamed/generalized.
  - `current_day_panel` became `buffer_panel`, which is now a `RollingPanel`
  - `prior_day_panel` became a dictionary mapping `Frequency` objects to
    "digest panels", which are instances of `RollingPanel`.
- Hard-coded daily rollover replaced with a notion of a "current window" for
   each unique frequency managed by the panel.
  - When the end of the current window is reached for a given frequency, we
    compute an aggregate bar (code refers to this as a "digest"), which is
    appended to a panel associated with that frequency.
  - Window rollover dates are managed by a pair of dictionaries,
    `cur_window_starts` and `cur_window_closes`.  The `Frequency` class is
    responsible for computing window bounds based on the open/close of the
    previous window.
- Semantic change to the `open_price` field: `open_price` now always
   contains the price of the first trade occurring in the given window.
   Previously it contained the price of the first minute in the window,
   returning NaN it the security happened not to trade in the first minute.
'

title: ENH: Filter out empty lists from `get_open_orders`.
body:
b'Filter out empty lists from `get_open_orders` so that we have consistent
behavior between the case where a user has never placed an order and the case
where the user has placed an order but it has been executed or cancelled.

A nice side-effect, which was the impetus for this change, is that you can
check if you have any open orders by doing:

```
len(get_open_orders()) == 0
```

Also adds a test for the behavior of `get_open_orders`, which was previously
lacking.
'

title: MAINT/PERF: Make the portfolio property call `updated_portfolio`.
body:
b"Make the portfolio property on TradingAlgorithm call `updated_portfolio`
internally.  This prevents needless recomputation of the portfolio between
calls to `handle_data`, and also prevents issues where the portfolio object
could be unexpectedly modified in place in the body of a `handle_date` call.

Also adds some optimizations to `PerformancePeriod.get_positions` to 
avoid needless insertions/deletions from the `Positions` object that's supplied
on the algo-facing portfolio.
"

title: ENH: Add trading controls to zipline API.
body:
b"Adds four new methods to the Zipline API that can be used as circuit-breakers
to interrupt the execution of an algorithm.  The API methods are:

`set_max_position_size`
`set_max_order_size`
`set_max_order_count`
`set_long_only`

Internally, these methods are implemented by each registering a TradingControl
callback object with the TradingAlgorithm.  During
TradingAlgorithm.__validate_order_params (and thus before any side-effects of
the order call occur), each callback's `validate` method is called with
information about the order to be placed and the algorithm's current state,
raising an exception if the callback detects that an error condition has been breached.
"

title: CLI
body:
b'Adds a CLI and IPython magic for zipline.

CLI example:

```
python run_algo.py -f dual_moving_avg.py --symbols AAPL --start 2011-1-1 --end 2012-1-1 -o dma.pickle
```

Grabs the data from yahoo finance, runs the file dual_moving_avg.py (and looks for dual_moving_avg_analyze.py which, if found, will be executed after the algorithm has been run), and outputs the perf dataframe to dma.pickle.

IPython magic command (at the top of an IPython notebook cell):

```
%%zipline --symbols AAPL --start 2011-1-1 --end 2012-1-1 -o perf
```

Does the same as above except instead of executing the file looks for the algorithm in the cell and instead of outputting the perf df to a file, creates a variable in the namespace called `perf`.
'

title: Transforms - ATR
body:
b"Hi.

I use ATR so frequently to size positions and set stops, limits, etc., that I thought it would be useful to have it as a simple transform, basically a property of the security.  The history doesn't matter, only the current value at the current point in time. 

For example, 

stop_price = data[stock].price - 2 \* data[stock].atr(20)

is much cleaner than:
# Set up the ATR indicator.
# atr_data = ta.ATR(timeperiod=20)

def handle_data(context, data):  
    ...
    stop_price = data[stock].price - 2 \* atr_data(data)[stock]

I had a go at the simple transform, but I'll need some guidance putting together the test.  Namely how do I set up my test data history of high, low and close prices to use for my assert calculations?

Thanks.
"

title: BUG: Trading calendar dates should always be midnight UTC
body:
b'For consistency, datetimes returned by the trading calendar should
always show HHMMSS of midnight UTC. Not only is this useful for
consistency, but it also allows us to check if a particular date() is
in an array of these datetimes, because they will hash to the same
thing. For example:

early_closes = get_early_closes()
... later ...
if current_bar_datetime.date() in early_closes:
    ... today closes early ...

If if the datetimes returned by the trading calendar functions don't
have 00:00:00 for HHMMSS, then the "in" check above will fail because
the date and the datetimes in early_closes won't hash to the same
thing.
'

title: Add a VirtualBox-based Vagrant config file.
body:
b'This is a very simple change to automate the building of a Zipline development environment using Vagrant (www.vagrantup.com).

This particular configuration requires VirtualBox, though I'm sure it could be customized to work with EC2 using the other Vagrant Provider (https://github.com/mitchellh/vagrant-aws). 

This VagrantFile will, on "vagrant up"...
- Create a simple, minimal Precise Pangolin (12.04) Ubuntu 64 bit VM
- Customize the VM with 2 virtual CPU's and 2048MB of RAM
- Configure SSH for passwordless access (from the command-line)
- Add the required packages from the Ubuntu repo to support zipline
- Add (and compile) ta-lib 
- Add the required Pip packages

This takes ~25 minutes on my fairly beefy macbook, mostly spent in downloading packages from the Ubuntu mirrors.

When Vagrant is done, you can start hacking on zipline with a ...
- vagrant ssh
- cd /vagrant
- python {some python script that uses zipline}

In the spirit of making this a disposable dev environment, I decided to forego configuring virtualenv and instead install everything in site-packages.

"nosetests" and "examples/dual_moving_average.py" both succeed after the configuration finishes.

Let me know if you have any questions!
'

title: Add support to specify delay between placing and filling an order.
body:
b"Blotter was called before handle_data() which only allowed filling at the next bar.

Here I moved it after handle_data() but added a delay to allow for the same behavior as before. If an option `fill_delay` is passed though this can be overridden.

Once this is in we can think about default values for daily mode.

There's one outstanding issue I'd like to get some feedback on (see code).
"

title: BUG: Fix updating of trading_days_total in minute.
body:
b'In the batch_transform we were incrementing the trading_days counter if there
is a new day event. Thus with a window_length of 1 and daily bars you will
update the batch_transform on the first day which is correct. But with minutes
you update with the first minute bar of the day which is not correct.

This is fixed by calculating the market_close explicity and seeing whether the
event.dt is on or past it.

I also added a unittest to test the correct behavior of this.
'

title: Support for TA-Lib transforms
body:
b'This PR adds support for TA-Lib transforms.

They are used like this:

``` python
import zipline.transforms.ta as ta
class Algo(TradingAlgorithm):
    def __init__(self, ...):
        sid = 'XYZ'
        self.close_ma = ta.MA(sid) # MA of closing price with default parameters
        self.high_ma = ta.MA(sid, close='high') # MA of high price with default parameters
        self.vix_ma = ta.MA(sid, close='vix', timeperiod=10) # MA of a data column called 'vix' with timeperiod of 10

    def handle_data(data):
        ma_result = self.close_ma.handle_data(data)

```

The `close=*` syntax might look weird at first. The reason for it is that the abstract functions of TA-Lib accept a dictionary with `open`, `high`, `low`, `close` and `volume` keys, and look to specific keys of that dict for data. For example, MA uses whatever data is stored under `close`. By passing an optional argument like `close = 'high'`, the user can instruct my transform to replace the default data of that key with something arbitrary that also exists in the dataframe. So `close='high'` tells Zipline "take whatever data is in the `high` column of my dataframe, and pass it to TA-Lib as the `close` field, because this transform uses `close` as its data source." As another example, the BETA transform uses the data in `high` and `low` as x and y, so users could pass `high='price', low='spx'` to calculate the beta of their sid's price against an arbitrary SPX data column.

The docstrings of the ta.\* objects are dynamic and reflect not only the TA-Lib and Zipline docs, but also any available keyword arguments and also the default data dictionary mappings (for example, the fact that MA will use the `close` field to get its 'price' input, or that BETA uses `high` and `low`). So `help(ta.MA)` is your friend here -- or `ta.MA?` for IPython users. 

For example, the top of the MA docstring:

``` python
"""
#---- TA-Lib docs

 MA(real[, timeperiod=?, matype=?])

    Moving average (Overlap Studies)

    Inputs:
        real: (any ndarray)
    Parameters:
        timeperiod: 30
        matype: 0 (Simple Moving Average)
    Outputs:
        real

#---- Default mapping (TA-Lib : Zipline)

        price : close

#---- Zipline docs

        TA-Lib keyword arguments must be passed at initialization. For
        example, to construct a moving average with timeperiod of 5, pass
        "timeperiod=5" during initialization.
"""
```

and the BETA docstring includes:

``` python
"""
#---- Default mapping (TA-Lib : Zipline)

        price0 : high
        price1 : low
"""
```

Many thanks to @mrjbq7, whose work on the python talib made this possible, also @twiecki and @ehebert for invaluable assistance.
'

This refactoring lead me to discover a small logic bug. We were before saying a window of e.g. size 3 to be full on the 4th event. Now it's full upon seeing the 3rd event. title: Add a function for downloading 10 year treasury data to use as a benchmark
body:
b"See #132

The 10 year treasury should be used as the benchmark. E.g. Investopedia states The 30-year Treasury used to be the bellwether U.S. bond but now most consider the 10-year Treasury to be the benchmark..

Besides the 10-year rate being the more common benchmark, it's also far easier to get better data for. Beginning February 18, 2002, Treasury ceased publication of the 30-year constant maturity series. On February 9, 2006, Treasury reintroduced the 30-year constant maturity. These 4 years of missing data makes it difficult to use as a benchmark. Right now zipline's logging is complaining vociferously about this missing data.
"

title: Rolling panel data structure
body:
b"This should be a good start for managing an iterative collection of DataFrames. Currently it's only:
- DatetimeIndex as the major axis of the panel (the index of each DataFrame)
- Fairly unsafe if the user might persist panels between calls to `get_current`

The performance on a pretty vanilla example (collection of 20 x 5 DataFrames, window size 100, 200 total periods) should be compelling. This is the time to construct the panels at each window for the full sample:

```
In [4]: %time f(option='naive')
CPU times: user 3.52 s, sys: 0.01 s, total: 3.53 s
Wall time: 3.52 s

In [5]: timeit f(option='clever')
10 loops, best of 3: 40.9 ms per loop
```

I think this is a good general strategy. Could be generalized for heterogeneous panels etc. if you wanted. 

EDIT A bit more color on performance. Doing 500 periods now and adding a panel-copy at each iteration if you want users to be able to mutate the panel to their heart's content:

```
In [3]: timeit f()
10 loops, best of 3: 99.2 ms per loop

In [4]: timeit f(copy=True)
10 loops, best of 3: 121 ms per loop

In [5]: %time f(option='naive')
CPU times: user 11.04 s, sys: 0.02 s, total: 11.06 s
Wall time: 11.10 s
```

So the copy overhead is fairly minimal but makes sense to be able to disable it if you want to squeeze out every drop of performance in some internal computation.
"

title: ENH: use array and pandas operations to speed up risk computations
body:
b"A few changes to start a conversation about performance in the performance and risk analytics in zipline.

I started with the pair trading example. Here's on `master` before the PR:

```
In [2]: %time results = pairtrade.run(data)
[2013-03-22 01:35] INFO: Performance: Simulated 2268 trading days out of 2268.
[2013-03-22 01:35] INFO: Performance: first open: 1993-01-04 14:30:00+00:00
[2013-03-22 01:35] INFO: Performance: last close: 2001-12-31 21:00:00+00:00
CPU times: user 30.32 s, sys: 0.14 s, total: 30.46 s
Wall time: 30.52 s
```

and after

```
In [2]: %time results = pairtrade.run(data)
[2013-03-22 01:33] INFO: Performance: Simulated 2268 trading days out of 2268.
[2013-03-22 01:33] INFO: Performance: first open: 1993-01-04 14:30:00+00:00
[2013-03-22 01:33] INFO: Performance: last close: 2001-12-31 21:00:00+00:00
CPU times: user 22.03 s, sys: 0.21 s, total: 22.23 s
Wall time: 22.24 s
```

Here's what the cProfile summary looks like right now:

```
         7556356 function calls (7433722 primitive calls) in 26.211 seconds

   Ordered by: cumulative time

   ncalls  tottime  percall  cumtime  percall filename:lineno(function)
        1    0.013    0.013   26.211   26.211 <string>:1(<module>)
        1    0.002    0.002   26.199   26.199 algorithm.py:156(run)
     2270    0.002    0.000   25.646    0.011 tradesimulation.py:108(simulate)
     2270    0.037    0.000   25.644    0.011 tradesimulation.py:233(transform)
        1    0.000    0.000   11.634   11.634 performance.py:329(handle_simulation_end)
        1    0.000    0.000   11.603   11.603 risk.py:680(__init__)
        4    0.016    0.004   11.603    2.901 risk.py:726(periods_in_range)
      414    1.809    0.004   11.582    0.028 risk.py:99(__init__)
     2269    0.017    0.000    9.761    0.004 performance.py:203(transform)
     4536    0.099    0.000    8.986    0.002 performance.py:239(process_event)
     2268    0.040    0.000    8.755    0.004 performance.py:277(handle_market_close)
      828    2.252    0.003    8.292    0.010 risk.py:208(calculate_period_returns)
     2268    0.077    0.000    8.039    0.004 risk.py:466(update)
     4536    4.282    0.001    4.282    0.001 risk.py:594(calculate_period_returns)
     2268    0.007    0.000    4.173    0.002 tradesimulation.py:305(simulate_snapshot)
     2268    0.016    0.000    4.161    0.002 <ipython-input-1-a540f760656c>:66(handle_data)
     2268    0.115    0.000    3.836    0.002 utils.py:406(handle_data)
      872    2.343    0.003    2.828    0.003 index.py:569(isin)
123316/123294    2.690    0.000    2.691    0.000 {numpy.core.multiarray.array}

2553/2552    0.045    0.000    1.864    0.001 index.py:146(__new__)
     3773    0.054    0.000    1.859    0.000 series.py:390(__new__)
    15126    0.166    0.000    1.554    0.000 index.py:88(__new__)
     6755    0.029    0.000    1.509    0.000 frame.py:347(__init__)
    56823    0.046    0.000    1.507    0.000 index.py:2610(_ensure_index)
     2682    0.045    0.000    1.392    0.001 risk.py:268(calculate_beta)
    13317    0.073    0.000    1.243    0.000 fromnumeric.py:32(_wrapit)
     2200    0.025    0.000    1.152    0.001 frame.py:476(_init_dict)

86006/85984    0.085    0.000    1.048    0.000 numeric.py:167(asarray)
      286    0.299    0.001    1.026    0.004 collections.py:103(keys)
     5364    0.031    0.000    1.010    0.000 risk.py:223(calculate_volatility)
      828    0.008    0.000    1.007    0.001 index.py:1264(normalize)
      896    0.016    0.000    0.995    0.001 tools.py:51(to_datetime)
      896    0.013    0.000    0.975    0.001 tools.py:72(_convert_f)
     2288    0.011    0.000    0.890    0.000 frame.py:2527(reindex)
      895    0.867    0.001    0.877    0.001 {pandas.tslib.datetime_to_datetime64}
     2703    0.011    0.000    0.870    0.000 shape_base.py:177(vstack)
```

To start making more progress on improving performance, several things probably should start happening:

1) Most of the risk and performance analytics need to get moved to Cython. Internal functions not exposed to end users should all be cdef'd

2) Time stamps should probably all be represented as `int64` values corresponding to the equivalent `datetime64` format used in pandas. You can find loads of support code for converting back and forth in `pandas/tslib.pyx` and supporting C files. This really isn't as awful as it sounds-- a few helper functions internally and you're in business.

3) No more lists for accumulating results. You should just adapt the approach that I use in `pandas/hashtable.pyx` of a simple Cython vector class which works very similarly to a C++ STL vector (doubles the size whenever it exceeds the length). Here is what one looks like:

```
cdef class Float64Vector:

    cdef:
        size_t n, m
        ndarray ao
        float64_t *data

    def __cinit__(self):
        self.n = 0
        self.m = _INIT_VEC_CAP
        self.ao = np.empty(_INIT_VEC_CAP, dtype=np.float64)
        self.data = <float64_t*> self.ao.data

    def __len__(self):
        return self.n

    def to_array(self):
        self.ao.resize(self.n)
        return self.ao

    cdef inline append(self, float64_t x):
        if self.n == self.m:
            self.m = self.m * 2
            self.ao.resize(self.m)
            self.data = <float64_t*> self.ao.data

        self.data[self.n] = x
        self.n += 1
```

I would recommend adding an alternate method to `to_array` that does not resize the array and simply returns a view up through the last appended element (just use python slicing. you can also use `PyArray_SimpleNewFromData`). 

4) The risk module should be refactored as the iterative risk report approach is very slow-- object construction and general Python interpreter overhead is dogging you bad, especially this method:

```
    def periods_in_range(self, months_per, start, end):
        one_day = datetime.timedelta(days=1)
        ends = []
        cur_start = start.replace(day=1)

        # in edge cases (all sids filtered out, start/end are adjacent)
        # a test will not generate any returns data
        if len(self.algorithm_returns) == 0:
            return ends

        #ensure that we have an end at the end of a calendar month, in case
        #the return series ends mid-month...
        the_end = advance_by_months(end.replace(day=1), 1) - one_day
        while True:
            cur_end = advance_by_months(cur_start, months_per) - one_day
            if(cur_end > the_end):
                break
            cur_period_metrics = RiskMetricsBatch(
                start_date=cur_start,
                end_date=cur_end,
                returns=self.algorithm_returns
            )

            ends.append(cur_period_metrics)
            cur_start = advance_by_months(cur_start, 1)

        return ends
```

Anyway, general conclusion: more NumPy, more vectorization, more Cython, fewer object instantiations, fewer `datetime.datetime` objects. Since a lot of these things are internal implementation details you don't have to break any APIs =)
"

title: WIP: ta-lib transforms
body:
b"This is a proposal template for ta-lib transforms, based on a conversation with Thomas earlier today. I haven't added all the functions yet, waiting for comments.

This design might look a little strange at first since it doesn't use the usual `@batch_transform` decorator. The reason is that `BatchTransform`s need a `window_length` specified, but so do (almost all) ta-lib functions. To have users do that twice is a source of potential confusion and also error. The wrapper I propose here uses the ta-lib arguments to figure out what the `window_length` should be, if possible, and set it.

Please let me know if you have any thoughts.
"

title: Changes the API for recording variables.
body:
b"Uses a method called 'record' that provides a key value,
instead of providing keys to extract from context.

The variables are stored internally to the algorithm in a dictionary,
and not just stared as a property of the algorithm.

Main intent behind this change is to make the API more user friendly,
since the previous recorded_variables relies on the value to be set
in the algorithms context/self, the hope is that only having to use
the `record` method means less moving pieces and a more understandable
API.

i.e., instead of:

```
def initialize(self):
    recorded_variables('foo', bar')

def handle_data(self, data):
    self.foo = 1
    self.bar = 2
```

The API is now:

```
def initialize(self):
    pass

def handle_data(self, data):
    self.record('foo', 1)
    self.record('bar', 2)
```
"

title: Fixed bugs in the sequence of dividend payment calculations.
body:
b'Previously, we were using midnight of the current trading day in market
close. That meant that we were "rewinding" the clock, and then checking the
ex_date and pay_date. As a result, we were delaying payments by one day.

With this patch, on the close of markets we "fast forward" to midnight of the
next trading day and calculate the dividend payments. This patch assumes that
the dividend dates are all at midnight UTC.
'

title: Recycles objects for portfolio and positions.
body:
b'Performance (speed) improvement in the `performance` module.

The creation of new portfolio and position objects on every event to pass to handle_data was incurring a large overhead.

This patch recycles the object used for each handle_data and sets new values, which speeds up performance by an order of magnitude. For a dataset that used to spend 5+ seconds in `as_portfolio`, the time spent is now under 0.5 seconds.
'

title: Recycles objects for portfolio and positions.
body:
b'Recycles the objects created to pass the portfolio and positions to handle_data.

Since these values are passed to every call to handle_data, the object
creation for each hit of this loop becomes a high overall cost.
Instead of creating on object on each pass, this patch uses the same object for each pass,
but changes the values contained with in before passing along to handle_data.

With some benchmarking, seeing a large order of magnitude gain.
i.e. in a data set where `as_portfolio` took over 5 seconds, when recycling values `as_portfolio` now takes under 0.5 seconds.

Also, changes the containing type of the positions to be a regular Python dict, since accessing the values inside of the ndict had too much of a penalty.
This changes the existing behavior when a position is being accessed when that position does not exist.
Previously, a position for that sid would be created, but with  zeroed out values (i.e. the default/starting values).
Code inside of handle_data will now have to check for existence of a position before accessing it.

i.e., previously:

```
position = context.portfolio.positions['STOCK']
```

Would return a value of `position` as the following:

```
ndict({'sid': 'STOCK',
         'cost_basis': 0.0,
         'last_sale_price': 0.0,
         'amount': 0})
```

Now, a handle_data that accesses positions, should wrap the call as such:

```
if 'STOCK' in context.portfolio.positions:
    position = context.portfolio.positions['STOCK']
```

or

```
try:
    position = context.portfolio.positions['STOCK']
except KeyError:
    log.info("No position held for 'STOCK'")
```
'

title: Enables performance messages on days that have no trades.
body:

event data to process for that day, performance metrics were
not emitted, since the handling was based on having an event
trigger the daily performance metric.

Handled by grouping together performance messages, on market open,
for all days since the last market close.

Also, changes perf_tracker unit test to simulate missing data.

Taken from @richafrank's branch handling the same case.
"

title: Changes tests from using an ndict for trades to an Event object.
body:
b"When run over large amounts of data the use of ndict's gets and sets
become a large bottleneck, around 1/5th of the CPU time is spent
in ndict's `__setattr__`, `__getattr__`, etc.

By switching to an object for an event,
we reduce the penalty significantly.

Removes asserts that check for event being an `ndict`, as well as those
that assume a certain behavior of the `__contains__` method for events.
"

You can now specify 

```

```

and it will only include those in the data panel. This is interesting for single-sid transforms (e.g. moving average), universe, and future risk.py refactoring.
"

title: Backtest end dates
body:
b"Risk and perf were doing their own date bookkeeping - now perf gives the current time to risk.

We were also moving the market day markers forward on the last day of the backtest, which blows up if the last day of the backtest is also the last day of data that we have.  So we don't do that anymore.

Related to that, we were calling handle_market_close an extra time at the end of the simulation, in case no events occurred on or after the last close.  Now we only do that when we know that's the case.
"

title: Allows the capital base of an algorithm to be more easily modified.
body:
b'By having run() use a capital_base member of the algorithm to
create the trading environment, the capital base should now be
configurable in the algorithms `initialize` method.

e.g.:

```
class LowCapitalBaseAlgorithm(TradingAlgorithm):

    def initialize(self):
        self.captial_base = 1000.0
```
'

title: ENH: batch_transform now adds arbitrary keys to datapanel.
body:
b"While trying to port another algorithm I wanted to add new, arbitrary fields to the batch_transform. This wasn't possible as we by default only add price and volume. It is quite trivial to just add everything we find in the event frame.

A user could, for example could now do:

```
for sid in sids:
    data[sid]['val'] = value
my_batch_transform(data)
```

And access the column 'val' inside of the data panel.
"

title: Handle missing historical data more elegantly
body:
b'Updated the search for treasury data when there is none for the test end date.  It could be that the end date is not a trading day, or we could just be missing treasury data.  In either case, we try to recover more gracefully now, by searching as far as possible and maybe logging a warning.

Similarly, if there is no benchmark data for the test end date, look for the next trading day.  If we really have no data, blow up with our own explicit exception, instead of overflowing in our search for dates in the future.
'

title: Slippage model bug
body:
b"The open orders list that gets passed to the slippage model was getting out of sync with the time/state of the user's algo.  This is because there is a generator pipeline something like:

date-sorted events -> slippage -> grouping by date -> algo

Grouping by date will pull from the pipline lazily, but it needs to know when the current group is full in order to pass it on to the algo.  Thus, it pulls the first of the next day's events, and then passes the current day's group to the algo.  The algo is now on the current day and updates the open orders, but the first of the next day's slippage results has already been pulled from the generator and was created using yesterday's open orders.

So I moved the grouping earlier in the pipeline:

date-sorted events -> grouping by date -> slippage -> algo

We're a little less lazy by grouping earlier, but I don't think that should impact the performance.  Any worries?
"

Currently using these ignores in the config file:

```
[pep8]
ignore = E124,E125,E126

Should address later.
